136067</a>. <a href="/wiki/Digital_object_identifier" title="Digital object identifier">doi</a>:<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//doi.org/10.1038%2F444534a">10.1038/444534a</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHistory+of+science&amp;rft.atitle=In+search+of+lost+time&amp;rft.aufirst=Jo&amp;rft.aulast=Marchant&amp;rft.date=2006&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Nature&amp;rft.pages=534-538&amp;rft.volume=444&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1038%2F444534a&amp;rft_id=info%3Apmid%2F17136067&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-28"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-28">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web"><a href="/wiki/Bill_Casselman_(mathematician)" title="Bill Casselman (mathematician)">Bill Casselman</a>. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.math.ubc.ca/~cass/Euclid/papyrus/papyrus.html">"One of the Oldest Extant Diagrams from Euclid"</a>. University of British Columbia<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">26 September</span> 2008</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHistory+of+science&amp;rft.au=Bill+Casselman&amp;rft.btitle=One+of+the+Oldest+Extant+Diagrams+from+Euclid&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.pub=University+of+British+Columbia&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.math.ubc.ca%2F~cass%2FEuclid%2Fpapyrus%2Fpapyrus.html&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-Boyer_Influence_of_the_Elements-29"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Boyer_Influence_of_the_Elements_29-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation book"><a href="/wiki/Carl_Benjamin_Boyer" title="Carl Benjamin Boyer">Boyer</a> (1991). "Euclid of Alexandria". <i>A History of Mathematics</i>. p.&#160;119. <q>The <i>Elements</i> of Euclid not only was the earliest major Greek mathematical work to come down to us, but also the most influential textbook of all times. [...]The first printed versions of the <i>Elements</i> appeared at Venice in 1482, one of the very earliest of mathematical books to be set in type; it has been estimated that since then at least a thousand editions have been published. Perhaps no book other than the Bible can boast so many editions, and certainly no mathematical work has had an influence comparable with that of Euclid\'s <i>Elements</i>.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHistory+of+science&amp;rft.atitle=Euclid+of+Alexandria&amp;rft.au=Boyer&amp;rft.btitle=A+History+of+Mathematics&amp;rft.date=1991&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.pages=119&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-30"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-30">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation book">Calinger, Ronald (1999). <i>A Contextual History of Mathematics</i>. Prentice-Hall. p.&#160;150. <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-02-318285-7" title="Special:BookSources/0-02-318285-7">0-02-318285-7</a>. <q>Shortly after Euclid, compiler of the definitive textbook, came Archimedes of Syracuse (c. 287\xe2\x80\x93212 BC.), the most original and profound mathematician of antiquity.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHistory+of+science&amp;rft.aufirst=Ronald&amp;rft.aulast=Calinger&amp;rft.btitle=A+Contextual+History+of+Mathematics&amp;rft.date=1999&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.isbn=0-02-318285-7&amp;rft.pages=150&amp;rft.pub=Prentice-Hall&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-31"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-31">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web">O\'Connor, J.J.; Robertson, E.F. (February 1996). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www-groups.dcs.st-and.ac.uk/~history/HistTopics/The_rise_of_calculus.html">"A history of calculus"</a>. <a href="/wiki/University_of_St_Andrews" title="University of St Andrews">University of St Andrews</a><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">7 August</span> 2007</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHistory+of+science&amp;rft.au=O%27Connor%2C+J.J.&amp;rft.au=Robertson%2C+E.F.&amp;rft.btitle=A+history+of+calculus&amp;rft.date=1996-02&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.pub=University+of+St+Andrews&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww-groups.dcs.st-and.ac.uk%2F~history%2FHistTopics%2FThe_rise_of_calculus.html&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-32"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-32">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www-history.mcs.st-and.ac.uk/history/Projects/Pearce/Chapters/Ch3.html">"3: Early Indian culture - Indus civilisation"</a>. <i>st-and.ac.uk</i>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHistory+of+science&amp;rft.atitle=3%3A+Early+Indian+culture+-+Indus+civilisation&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=st-and.ac.uk&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww-history.mcs.st-and.ac.uk%2Fhistory%2FProjects%2FPearce%2FChapters%2FCh3.html&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-33">